Because self-marriage isn’t legal, sologamists are free to also marry someone else down the line if they want to. 

But they say that possibility shouldn't negate the importance of their relationships with themselves.

https://t.co/j24l1vRkVl https://t.co/zhuCx63lI7

Fun is a big part of the proposition for sologamists, who don't think extravagant ceremonies should be limited to couples.

But not everyone feels the need for a big solo wedding. After all, self-marriage is first and foremost about committing to oneself.

https://t.co/j24l1vRkVl https://t.co/wCyHPT4F6s

Some celebrities have also embraced sologamy. 

Fantasia Barrino married herself before she met her husband, and Emma Watson once called herself "self-partnered." In 2017, model Adriana Lima explained she wore a diamond because it was symbolic.

https://t.co/j24l1vRkVl https://t.co/Lhw7qz0RsY

After learning about sologamy online, Ghia Vitale proposed to herself in her bedroom. 

It's her way of rebelling against the institution of marriage and traditional relationship norms that she doesn’t agree with, she said. 

https://t.co/j24l1vRkVl https://t.co/mgI8Udh6Yl

Palmonia Gordon had promised herself that if she wasn't married by the time she was 50, she would "have a big old celebration." 

On her 50th birthday, she donned a gown and married herself at the Casablanca Hotel in Niagara Falls. 

https://t.co/j24l1vRkVl https://t.co/J8nsMj9a4U

During the pandemic, Nneka Carter endured months away from friends and family. 

As a single woman, she had to remind herself that she could get through that difficult time on her own. Ultimately, she decided to affirm that strength by marrying herself. 

https://t.co/j24l1vRkVl https://t.co/CsILhDQg6Z

That was the case for Ena Jones, who married herself in September 2020.

Her big day included 20 guests, a white wedding gown, a tiara, a wedding cake covered in sunflowers, and plenty of tears.

https://t.co/j24l1vRkVl https://t.co/TvvcC1jPYl

But the trend has definitely picked up since COVID-19 hit. 

Singles, fortified by homebound self-discovery, have come to realize that they are their own best companions — and that healthy relationships require them to be comfortable with themselves.

https://t.co/j24l1vRkVl https://t.co/wcfXVU1kd7

Self-marriage isn't a binding, legal affair. You don't get a tax break, and you're free to marry someone else in the future without officially divorcing yourself. 

As a result, it's hard to track exactly how many women have committed to themselves.

https://t.co/j24l1vRkVl

https://t.co/I9kTXJwXnK

https://t.co/I9kTXJwXnK https://t.co/PM7XxFqMEN

As he got more into his own fitness journey, Hamilton realized he wanted to help others with disabilities take ownership of their health, so he created Disabled but Not Really.

https://t.co/I9kTXJwXnK https://t.co/eOEMoopBEN

But that changed after the shooting. He came to view himself as capable of far more and began to overhaul his lifestyle.

https://t.co/I9kTXJwXnK https://t.co/iOuXMSqtae

Before the shooting, Hamilton had just gotten sole custody of his daughter, who was then 2 years old. As a single dad he was working full time to support her even though he hadn't fully let go of the street life. 

https://t.co/I9kTXJwXnK

Hamilton, whose story was highlighted on season four of @QueerEye in 2019, told Insider that while he was growing up his only role models were drug dealers.

https://t.co/I9kTXJwXnK https://t.co/sPccTyaCog

Hamilton told Insider his effort to get in shape after the shooting gave him ownership over not only his health but also his life.

https://t.co/I9kTXJwXnK

He was already overweight before the shooting, but, depressed with his current state, he resolved to change his circumstances. While on bed rest, he took nutrition courses at a community college and put what he learned into action.

https://t.co/I9kTXJwXnK https://t.co/2iLDr7T99K

Hamilton was bedridden for a year as he recovered from the shooting, which caused him to develop an ulcer on his tailbone that required six surgeries. It took another two years of bed rest to recover from the procedures.

https://t.co/I9kTXJwXnK

But, as Hamilton told Insider, the moment ultimately proved liberating.

https://t.co/I9kTXJwXnK https://t.co/1nK3EqDtFy

https://t.co/I9kTXJwXnK

A 2012 shooting left @WesSpeaksLife paralyzed from the waist down. As he healed over the following years the incident ultimately proved liberating. 

Hamilton — who had grown up as a self-described "bad boy" — thought he'd never make it past 21 anyway. 👇

The pandemic is still ongoing, but conditions are better than they were a year from today.

And "Dry January" just might help.

https://t.co/0cnAU36eaJ

Research also suggests that more millennials participate in "Dry January" in larger numbers than their older counterparts, with alcohol purchases decreasing at the beginning of the year and increasing by February. 

https://t.co/0cnAU2ODjb

Data shows that younger people may be leading the brigade to drink less.
 
Millennials and Gen Zers have been consuming less than older generations in recent years. 📉

https://t.co/0cnAU2ODjb

"Dry January" speaks to the larger "sober-curious" movement that is growing in popularity among young people. 

As Insider reported in November, non-alcoholic beverage sales surged 33% to $331 million last year, according to @nielsen. 💸

https://t.co/0cnAU2ODjb https://t.co/x2pLJ3fAVX

A range of experts back the movement.

Even just reducing the amount of alcohol consumed has significant benefits to a person's physical health and mental well-being. 

https://t.co/0cnAU2ODjb

Though alcohol consumption increased this year, "Dry January" isn't ruled out for many Americans.

Polls from @MorningConsult and @YouGov found that as many as 15% of Americans, or one in seven, took a break from alcohol in January 2021.

https://t.co/0cnAU2ODjb https://t.co/wwzZ4aw7DB

The increase impacts collective health in the US. 🏥

Even a short-term consumption increase will result in an estimated 8,000 additional deaths from liver disease by 2040, per Massachusetts General Hospital.

But there's still room to turn things around.

https://t.co/0cnAU2ODjb

📈 Alcohol consumption overall has surged during the pandemic.

⚡️ “Codex Seraphinianus — the weirdest book in the world — just turned 40. We talked to its creator.” by @InsiderLife https://t.co/E21gj9j5DF

Serafini continues to work in mediums from sculpture to furniture design to architecture, theatre scenery, and costumes. 

As for now, he has two or three ideas about what he’ll do next and suggests a new edition of the Codex at some point in the future. 
https://t.co/D2e5Q3zZKp https://t.co/v8ojTHil4M

The trait that ultimately demonstrates the power of the Codex Seraphinianus is how it speaks to the subconscious. “Readers” might not understand what they’re seeing, but on some level they experience a connection to something, even if it’s an alien one.

https://t.co/D2e5Q3zZKp https://t.co/lJCQYNBaGe

Serafini has never given his invented language a name but says it has no sound. However, his calligraphy and images share a similar power to wordless music. 

https://t.co/D2e5Q3zZKp https://t.co/PP81DjrfJ0

@Rizzoli_Books published an expanded version in Italy in 2006, but it wasn’t until 2013 that the book became available again in America.

Released last month, the new 40th edition contains 18 new plates. Because, as it turns out, Serfini never stopped drawing. https://t.co/eA5ON7PvrJ

Published in 1981 in Italy as a two-volume affair, the Codex was later reprinted as a single volume in the US, Germany, and the Netherlands. Few copies were made, and it remained out of print until 1993, when Ricci published a new edition. 

https://t.co/D2e5Q3zZKp

Serafini didn’t want to put his name on the book, but they eventually compromised, with “Serafini” becoming “Seraphinianus” to sound more Latin. There was no real byline in those early prints, but Serafini hand-signed the first editions. 

https://t.co/D2e5Q3zZKp https://t.co/HanK19ngyW

It was Milan-based art publisher Franco Maria Ricci who came up with the idea of calling the work a Codex, something that summoned a connection to Leonardo da Vinici’s legendary Codex Atlanticus. 

https://t.co/D2e5Q3zZKp

Though his images are often grotesque or disturbing, Serafini’s vibrant colored pencils can render them soft and whimsical. 

Serafini, for his part, didn’t exactly know what he was setting out to do in creating the Codex. 

https://t.co/D2e5Q3zZKp https://t.co/1WRsUnayeQ

Serafini, 72, began creating his Codex in the mid-1970s. 

It’s like something you’d find on a shelf in Dr. Strange’s library — an arcane artifact that’s recognizably a book, just not one from our reality.

https://t.co/D2e5Q3zZKp https://t.co/TQNtD2zsMA

The weirdest book in the world — that no one can read — just turned 40. 

Italian artist Luigi Serafini gives @thisisinsider a look inside the 40th anniversary edition of his beautifully bizarre Codex Seraphinianus. ⬇️
